nce against an oppressive regime? Are the courts always the guardians of democracy and rule of law? What role was there for international law? How did the courts deal with dismissals, new appointees, new courts, forced German ordinances versus national law? How did judges justify their actions, help citizens, appease the enemy, protest against injustice? Experts from all democracies that were occupied by the Nazis paint vivid pictures of oppression, collaboration, and resistance. The results are interpreted in a socio-legal framework introducing the concept of 'moral hygiene' to explain the clash between normative and descriptive approaches in public opinion and scholarship concerning officials' behaviour in war-time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aConflict and Peace. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLaw. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aJudiciary, enemy occupation, second World War, National Socialism, collaboration.1 aArtuso, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaruch, Marc Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBost, Mélanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraver, Hans Petter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrilli, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLöhnig, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillon, Clément, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuller, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPe